properties.Name: Catedral de Tui
properties.description: The cathedral began to be built in 1120, although it would not be consecrated until 1225, in the time of King Alfonso IX. It has the appearance of a fortification, especially because of its crenellated towers. Its structure is clearly Romanesque, although later various decorative Gothic elements were added. The Romanesque capitals that top the interior columns stand out, while the Gothic portico of the main entrance stands out.

properties.Name: Convento de Santo Domingo
properties.description: Founded in 1330, the present construction was begun in the 15th century and concluded in 1524. Its church is a Gothic building with a nave of three bays (rebuilt in neoclassical style in the 18th century), a pronounced transept and triple apse, with robust exterior buttresses. The vaults are groined and ribbed. The main façade, neoclassical, has a bell tower, while the portal of the southern arm of the transept is Gothic, with pointed archivolts. The cloister has been modernly rebuilt. As for the sculpture, it is worth mentioning the corbels (heads of beams) of Romanesque tradition that support the cornice, as well as the bas-reliefs of the Gothic doorway, with a scene of the Epiphany in its tympanum.

properties.Name: Real Basílica de Santa María a Maior
properties.description: It is an example of the Elizabethan Gothic style buildings. It was built in the 16th century, commissioned by the Fishermen's Guild. Its authors are Joao Noble and Cornelius de Holanda. It has been a minor basilica since 1962, the year in which Pope John XXIII granted it this title. The west facade, work of C. de Holanda, is made in the form of an altarpiece, with three profusely decorated bodies. On the south façade there is an immense transept and the doorway opens under a semicircular arch, bordered by a stone jamb and baroque decorations. The interior consists of three naves separated by columns. The altarpiece of the High Altar, made of chestnut and walnut wood, dates from the late nineteenth and early twentieth century, and is the work of a cabinetmaker and carver santiagués. To the left of the south door is the sculpture of the Christ of the Good Journey, to whom devotees turn to for protection in the journeys they are about to undertake.

properties.Name: Iglesia de la Virgen Peregrina
properties.description: It is located next to the Gothic church of the former convent of San Francisco, next to the Portuguese Way of St. James. Erected between 1778 and 1832 according to plans by Antonio de Souto and Bernardo José de Mier -typical of the late Baroque with neoclassical elements-, its greatest originality lies in its scallop-shell plan and its convex façade, flanked by two towers. The nave itself, topped by the sacristy, is in the shape of a cross. It is preceded by an atrium with staircase and pinnacle balustrade, and presided over by an image (19th century) of the Virgen de la Peregrina, patron saint of the city and province of Pontevedra. The main altarpiece, neoclassical, was made in 1789 by Melchor de Prado.

properties.Name: Monasterio de San Salvador de Lérez
properties.description: Located very close to the city of Pontevedra, this former Benedictine monastery, which is known as early as the ninth century, offers interesting neoclassical and baroque elements.The monastery church, from the eighteenth century, is neoclassical in design and consists of a single nave with arches and vaults. Its facade, dated 1748, is however typical of the late Baroque. It is flanked by two towers. Inside, the chapel of San Benito (1700), which houses a Romanesque image of the Savior, stands out. Attached to the church is one of the galleries of the old Renaissance cloister from the 16th century. Several outbuildings of the old convent are also preserved. Every July 11, the monastery is the scene of the traditional popular pilgrimage of San Benito, with which the summer festive cycle of the city of Pontevedra begins.

The Tower of Hercules is located between the Orzán inlet and the Ártabro gulf. It is a Roman lighthouse of the ancient Brigantium. It dates from the second century AD, the time of Trajan, and was renovated in 1788 by order of King Charles IV. It was the work of the Lusitanian architect Gaius Sergius Lupo. It has a square floor plan, measures 68 meters and the light it gives off can be seen in the sea from a distance of 32 miles. The tower is divided into three successively narrower sections until it reaches the lantern. You have to climb a total of 242 steps to reach the top of the lighthouse, but the effort is worth it as you can see a magnificent view of the city and the coast of A Coruña. According to mythology, Hercules cut off Geryon's head and erected the monument after burying his mortal remains underneath.
properties.Name: Torre de Hércules
Torreón de Andrade
properties.description: It was built by Fernán Pérez de Andrade and dominates the entire valley of Pontedeume. Its tower of homage is square, covered by a vault of ashlar masonry and topped with battlements and machicolations.

properties.Name: Iglesia de Santa María de Cambre
properties.description: The church has a basilica plan, with three naves divided into four sections. It has a transept and chancel with an ambulatory open to five chapels, covered with barrel vaults. It is of Romanesque style, built in the 12th century under the patronage of the Traba family. In the windows of the main facade they used poly-lobed arches. The tympanum depicts an Agnus Dei carried by angels.

properties.Name: Iglesia de San Francisco de Betanzos
properties.description: It was rebuilt in the fourteenth century on a building of the thirteenth century. It has a Latin cross plan, single nave and apsidal chapels, its roof is gabled. Externally it is distributed in staggered heights. In the upper part there are three windows. The main doorway is pointed, its archivolts decorated with vegetal and geometric motifs. The tympanum depicts the theme of the Adoration of the Kings and the reception by St. Francis of the stigmata on Mount La Verna. At the foot of the temple is the Sarcophagus of Fernán Pérez de Andrade. It was declared a National Monument in 1919. At present it is of Cultural Interest.
